 past and its present, a tradition that has been carried on by more contemporary writers. This is the first book-length study devoted to modern German "author-as-character" fiction set in the Age of Goethe. It shows for thefirst time in a sustained manner the powerful hold the Goethezeit continues to exercise on the imagination of many of Germany's leading writers. This inner-German dialogue across the ages provides an important corrective to the dominant critical view that contemporary German-language literature is composed primarily under the sign of both globalization and the influence of mass American culture. The book will be of interest to both scholars of theGoethezeit and of contemporary German literature and culture. John D. Pizer is Professor of German and Comparative Literature at Louisiana State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors in literature. 0aBiographical fiction, GermanxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey18th centuryxAppreciationzGermany. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHistorical drama, GermanxHistory and criticism. 0aHistorical fiction, GermanxHistory and criticism. 0aKünstlerromanexHistory and criticism. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAge of Goethe.  aGerman culture.  aauthor-as-character fiction.  aglobalization.  ainner-German dialogue.  amass American culture.  amodern German literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113816340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571138163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571138163/original  a9